<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-10-22T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-10-22T06:00:00-05:00" n="236" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d236">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/1304: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>[, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-10-22T19:00:00+08:00">October 22, 1930—7
                                p.m.</date>]<lb/>[Received October 22—11:35
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>923. Following from American Consul at Hong Kong: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“October 22, 1 p.m. Father McGillicuddy of Catholic Mission at
                                    Kanchow informs me that the eight Americans in Kanchow including
                                    Bishop O’Shea and Fathers Cahill, Strauble, Curtis, Erbe,
                                    McLaughlin, Young and Moehringer, were last heard from by letter
                                    dated October 9th stating they desired to leave but were unable
                                    to do so safely. He is unable to get messages through to
                                    wireless station at Kanchow and is alarmed for their safety in
                                    view of reported Communist capture of Kian. I have informed
                                    Canton only.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
